Introduction

With student loan debt skyrocketing in recent years, many families in the US are struggling to pay off the student loan. This project aims to provide information on two sides of this problem. For families that potentially want to take a student loan, they need a clear picture of how the student loan is going to affect the family financially in the future. Not being able to pay back the loan is an apparent indicator of financial hardship, but what are the other financial struggles they are going through? For US government or policy-makers to make better policies to relieve the burden of student loans on family, and to make education more accessible for future students, they need to know what kind of families are more likely to have a high student loan amount, so they design a better plan to fit the families or adjust the bar for entering an affordable plans.

To provide information for both sides, this project is consists of two parts. The first part is finding which features of a family can predict the amount of student loans, among them which one has the biggest impact. The second part is to identify which financial hardship the education loan most likely leads to.

Problem Statement and Background

Affordability of student loans is a rising topic in the United States in recent years. The expense of education tuition fee keeps rising every year but it does not stop Americans from borrowing money to go to school. Today, more than 44 million people carry over $1.5 trillion of outstanding student loan debt, an amount that exceeds all other types of non-mortgage loan debt. While it is good to see that people attach more importance to education, and are willing to take a risk for academic advancement. However, many found themselves stuck in an unexpected financial hardship after getting a student loan. The U.S. Department of Education reports that about 20 percent of borrowers are in defaulttypically defined as having gone at least 270 days without a paymentmillions more are behind on their payments, and more than a million loans go into default each year. Federal student loans represent more than 92% of the outstanding student loan balance and the loans are guaranteed by the federal reserve, which means defaulted loans can also have a huge impact on the nations economy. Many families in the US are in student loan debt, but not every family can pay off their student loan easily. So why do American families taking student loan even though they it might heavily affect them in the future? The problem lies in the little information family has about the relationship between education loan and family situations.

The Pew Charitable Trusts published a report on Student Loan System Presents Repayment Challenges in 2019, in which it conducted an analysis of 400,0000 people in Texas who are in student debt, and found out that approximately a quarter of borrowers defaulted within five years of entering repayment. It found out that many are in distress and are struggling to pay back the loan. 21% of people owed more than before due to late payment. The thesis student loan debt and house household financial hardship: analysis using the 2016 survey of consumer finances concluded that student loan contributes to household financial hardship, using the same dataset this project uses. This project, however, focuses on the correlation between family features and student loan amount, and the correlation between student loan amount and financial hardship indicators.

Data

The data for this project comes from The Survey of Consumer Finances in 2016 ( which can be downloaded here https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/scfindex.htm). The Survey of Consumer Finances(SFC) is a dataset which contains all the data needed for the analysis and is provided by The Federal Reserve, the central bank of the United States for the purpose of helping the government and ultimately the public to understand the financial condition of families in the United States and to study the effects of changes in the economy. This data is based on a survey of six thousand households in the US about their finance. All the variables in the dataset are survey questions, the unit of observations is American household, every answer to the survey question is documented as the value. For the purpose of simplifying the dataset, all the questions and answers are documented in code and numbers. Therefore, the dataset comes with a codebook, which can also be downloaded on the same website. In total, there are 31240 observations and 5320 variables. For the first part of the project, I chose 15 variables as predictors of student loan amount. They are: Highest received education, Confidence in the US economy, Knowledge about own finance, Loan amount, Willingness to take financial risk, How many loans, Owe money to purchase property, Trust fund, Main bank account balance, Income, Life insurance, Balance of saving account, Value of certificate of deposit, Value of saving bonds, Market value of stock neutral funds. These are the financial indicators of a family. Additionally to predictors, basic demographic characteristics variables are also selected, including Age, Race, Gender of the head of the family, Marital status and Kind of housing. These variables are not used as predictors but the relationships between them and student loan amounts are graphed. For the second part of the project, I chose 6 variables to present financial hardship. They are Loan amount, Credit denied, Late debt payment, Payday loan, Bankruptcy, Foreclosure. These variables are chosen based on the belief that they can well represent the financial hardship that a family faces.

When it comes to data wrangling, most of the work focuses on interpreting the codebook. According to the codebook, I selected the above variables, rename all the columns as their original meanings. For categorical values, I also renamed them based on their meanings. Some answers in the survey are not applicable or answered with dont know/not sure, and they were given the value of 0 in the dataset. These values are treated as missing value for the analysis and are turned into N/A during the data wrangling stage.

Analysis

The first step for analysis is to find the relationship between the dependent variable (student loan amount) and independent variables. For categorical variables such as race, marital status, ****, which cannot be assigned to a certain level of loan amount relevance, I graphed their relationships to give a clear illustration of the difference of student loan amount between different groups.

loan_frequency

pie

The second step is to prepare the dataset for machine learning, which means I partition the dataset into the training set and the testing set. The training set is 75% of the data, which I use to investigate and train models. The testing set has 25% of the data, which I use to test out the accuracy of the model prediction. In order to find the best fitting model, I first preprocess the training data. The purpose of data preprocessing is to scale and transform the continuous variables, so the data can fall within the same numerical range; to impute the missing data for better-estimated results; to turn categorical variables into dummy variables to fit into the model in the next step. With the help of Cran package, a framework for creating and preprocess design matrices, I transform the variables to have a mean of 0 and variance of 1; impute the missing data and transformed categorical data. These changed are also applied to both training data and testing data in order to calculate out of sample predictions.
